====Homophones====
*[[sine]]

===Etymology===
From Latin '''[[signum]]''', ''sign''

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# (''sometimes also used uncountably'') A visible [[indication]].
#: ''Their angry expressions were a clear '''sign''' they didn't want to talk.''
#: ''Those clouds show '''signs''' of raining soon.''
#: ''Those clouds show little '''sign''' of raining soon.''
# A clearly visible object, generally flat, bearing a short message in words or pictures.
#: ''The '''sign''' in the window said "for rent".''
# A [[traffic sign]].
#: ''I missed the '''sign''' at the corner so I took the wrong turn.''
# A meaningful [[gesture]].
#: ''I gave them a thumbs-up '''sign'''.''
# Any of several specialized non-alphabetic [[symbol]]s.
#: ''The sharp '''sign''' indicates that the pitch of the note is raised a half step.''
# An [[astrological sign]].
#: ''Your '''sign''' is Taurus? That's no surprise.''
# {{mathematics}} Positive or negative polarity.
#: ''I got the magnitude right, but the '''sign''' was wrong.''
# A linguistic unit in [[sign language]] equivalent to [[word]] in spoken [[language]]s.
#: ''What's the '''sign''' for "computer"?''
# {{uncountable}} [[sign language]] in general
#: ''Sorry, I don't know '''sign''' very well.''
# An [[omen]].
#: ''"It's a '''sign''' of the end of the world," the doom prophet said.''

